		<hr />
		
		
		
		
		<div>Read this review Dolby, again from THG - <br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.tomshardware.com/2006/09/25/green_machine/" target="_blank">http://www.tomshardware.com/2006/09/25/green_machine/</a><br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				The Core 2 Duo platform drew significantly more power than the similarly-performing Athlon 64 X2 4600+ Energy Efficient system at both idle and maximum CPU load.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
The EE version (65W) of the 4200+ is less than $5 more than the 89W version.  And there is an even bigger spread on the idle power versus full draw, if you read the review fully.  Intel seems to have the power stable across the board, but you don't rev back nearly as much in idle states.<br />
<br />
What they are saying about how Intel is pushing out the 4x cores is that the cores are not 100% independent, either.  You will power up/use 2 cores at a time, so if you only need 2 cores you are good, but if you need 3 you have to fully power up the 4th core as well.  AMD's early chip designs are showing they have 4 fully independent cores in the system, and can power up/down cores individually as needed.  More important for server farms than home PC's for sure, but very interesting to see what is happening.<br />
<br />
Again, the sharkey's guide that I"m referring to has both an Intel and an AMD version clearly listed for processor and motherboard decisions.  I'm just an nVidia/AMD fan overall, so I stuck with what I'm comfortable with, and the guide came out with a good machine that took me about an hour to put together.  And for me, I find that working out what pieces work with each other to come up with a good system (and figuring out why stuff DOESN"T work after you build it) takes more time than the actual build.  This guide definitely took a lot of that work off of my hands, and I'm quite pleased with the system that I got from it.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.sharkeyextreme.com/guides/MVGSBG/article.php/3633106" target="_blank">http://www.sharkeyextreme.com/guide...cle.php/3633106</a></div>
	</td>
