		<hr />
		
		
		
		
		<div>Hey Grant,<br />
<br />
Both AMD and Intel processors will do fine and honestly you are probably not going to notice much difference between the two. Right now from a price for performce perspective the Intel Core 2 Duo is much better then the Athlon X2. The Athlon will get better performance on lower energy, if that matters to you.<br />
<br />
However, either way you go it would probably be better to wait about a month. Both Intel and AMD are close to luanching their 4 core chips. This will of course drive down the price of the dual core chips.<br />
<br />
I can't answer your question morthboard from an Intel standpoint as honestly I don't buy Intel ships.<br />
<br />
But, from an AMD standpoint. I've using an nForce250 based motherboard and its been doing fine. <br />
<br />
When you are selecting a motherboard look at what other hardware you want to upgrade. If you are getting a brand new processor and brand new motherboard its more then likely going to have PCIe 16 and no AGP slot so your Video card would need to be upgraded also. If you are carrying over the ram make sure its supported on the new board. If you want to go to SATA drives then make the motherboard has SATA.<br />
<br />
There are hundreds of motherboard variety's out there now and there really is no wrong answer there. Basically find a board in your price with your features and then read reviews on it. Then base your decision off of that.</div>
	</td>
</tr>
